Prompt: 'What is considered a high blood pressure reading?\n' 
Generated text: "It should be under 160/100.  I'm surprised you've never been tested.  It's normal to get your blood pressure checked every few years unless you have a chronic illness, but if you're between 18-30, that's the only time you need to be concerned."

Prompt: 'What are the risks of having high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: '\nThe risk of heart disease is 2 to 6 times greater if you have high blood pressure, compared to people with normal blood pressure.\n\nHigh blood pressure is often referred to as the “silent killer” because it often has no symptoms. High blood pressure can damage blood vessels, heart, kidneys, and eyes. Most people who have high blood pressure don’t know that they have it.\n\nThere are no signs or symptoms of high blood pressure. Blood pressure increases when the heart pumps more blood with each heartbeat.\n\nHow is high blood pressure measured?\n\nBlood pressure is measured using a sphygmomanometer. This is a device that measures the pressure in the arteries (blood vessels) during a blood pressure measurement.\n\nThe systolic pressure is the pressure in the artery when the heart beats. The diastolic pressure is the pressure in the artery when the heart is between beats.\n\nA normal blood pressure reading is between 120/80 mm Hg and 140/90 mm Hg. This is a systolic pressure of 120 and a diastolic pressure of 80. A person with high blood pressure has systolic and diastolic pressures of 140 and 90.\n\nHow common is high blood pressure?\n\nAbout 50% of people in the United States have high blood pressure. In Canada, about 60% of adults have high blood pressure.\n\nThere are several factors that affect how likely you are to have high blood pressure. These factors include:\n\nAge. People over age 65 have a much higher risk of high blood pressure than people under age 65.\n\nRace. African-Americans have a much higher risk of high blood pressure than white people.\n\nGender. Women have a much higher risk of high blood pressure than men.\n\nFamily history. People with a family history of high blood pressure are more likely to have high blood pressure.\n\nGenetics. Many people have genes that can cause high blood pressure. These genes do not cause high blood pressure on their own, but they increase the risk of having high blood pressure.\n\nDiagnosis\n\nHigh blood pressure is often called a “silent killer” because there are often no signs or symptoms. It’s called high blood pressure because it puts extra stress on blood vessels. If high blood pressure is not treated, it can damage blood vessels, heart, kidneys, and eyes.\n\nThe first sign of high blood pressure is usually a problem with vision or headaches. Other signs of high blood pressure include:\n\nChest pain\n\nShortness of breath\n\nNumbness or tingling in the hands, feet, or face\n\nSudden vision loss\n\nVision problems\n\nSwelling in the arms, face, and legs\n\nSudden weight gain or loss\n\nSudden headaches\n\nSudden weakness\n\nHeart failure\n\nStroke\n\nKidney failure\n\nHeart attack\n\nIf you have any of these symptoms, you should see your health care provider immediately.\n\nTreatment for high blood pressure\n\nHigh blood pressure can lead to serious health problems. Treating high blood pressure can reduce the risk of heart disease, heart attack, stroke, and kidney failure.\n\nBlood pressure medications can lower blood pressure, reduce the risk of heart attack, stroke, and kidney disease. Some blood pressure medications can lower blood pressure enough to prevent heart failure.\n\nThe best way to treat high blood pressure is to monitor it regularly. People with high blood pressure should have their blood pressure checked at least once a year. A blood pressure monitor should be used to check blood pressure at home.\n\nBlood pressure can be measured with a sphygmomanometer. This is a device that measures the pressure in the arteries (blood vessels) during a blood pressure measurement.\n\nSome blood pressure monitors can also measure heart rate and other important blood measures.\n\nBlood pressure medications may be prescribed for people with high blood pressure. These medications can lower blood pressure and reduce the risk of health problems. Some blood pressure medications can also lower blood pressure enough to prevent heart failure.\n\nThe blood pressure medications most often prescribed to treat high blood pressure are:\n\nDiuretics. Diuretics are drugs that make the kidneys produce more urine. This makes it easier to get rid of excess fluid and blood that builds up in the body.\n\nAngiotensin II receptor blockers. Angiotensin II receptor blockers are drugs that relax blood vessels. This reduces the force with which blood forces through the blood vessels.\n\nACE inhibitors. ACE inhibitors are drugs that relax blood vessels. This reduces the force with which blood forces through the blood vessels.\n\nBeta blockers. Beta blockers are drugs that relax blood vessels. This reduces the force with which blood forces through the blood vessels.\n\nVasodilators. Vasodilators are drugs that increase the flow of blood in the body.'

Prompt: 'What lifestyle changes can help prevent and lower high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: 'Here are some lifestyle changes you can make to help prevent high blood pressure:\n1. Eat less salt.\nPeople with high blood pressure tend to have higher blood pressure in general. Salt is a common cause of high blood pressure, so cutting back on salt can help lower your blood pressure.\nTry to cut back on processed and packaged foods that are full of sodium. Salt is a major contributor to high blood pressure, so limiting your salt intake can help you control your blood pressure.\n2. Get plenty of potassium.\nPotassium is an electrolyte that regulates the balance of water and sodium in your blood. If you don’t have enough potassium, you can have high blood pressure.\nTo get more potassium in your diet, try to eat foods that are high in potassium. Foods like bananas, avocados, and potatoes are good sources of potassium.\n3. Limit alcohol.\nEating enough potassium is important, but so is limiting alcohol intake. Alcohol can cause increased fluid retention, which can lead to swelling of the veins. This can put extra pressure on your heart.\n4. Keep an eye on your weight.\nPeople with high blood pressure tend to be overweight. Excess weight can raise blood pressure and lead to other health problems. Keep an eye on your weight by eating a diet that is high in fruits and vegetables, lean meats, and whole grains.\n5. Exercise regularly.\nRegular exercise helps you control your weight, but it also helps you manage high blood pressure. Try to get at least 30 minutes of exercise most days of the week.\nExercise can help lower your blood pressure and boost your heart health. It can also help you manage stress.\n6. Manage stress.\nStress can cause high blood pressure. It can also make it hard to manage your blood pressure. Finding ways to reduce stress in your life can help lower your blood pressure.\nOther lifestyle changes include eating a balanced diet, getting enough sleep, and limiting caffeine and smoking. Eating a diet high in fruits and vegetables can lower your cholesterol and blood pressure.\nIf you notice any changes in your body, you should see your doctor. Your doctor can help you get your blood pressure under control.'

Prompt: 'What kind of medicines can help control high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: '\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nSome common medicines to help control high blood pressure include diuretics, blood pressure medications, ACE inhibitors and beta-blockers. Diuretics, which help to remove excess water from the body, can help to lower blood pressure by increasing urine output. Blood pressure medications can help lower blood pressure by reducing the force of blood on the blood vessels. ACE inhibitors and beta-blockers help to relax blood vessels and reduce the force of blood on the blood vessels, which also decreases blood pressure.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nACE inhibitors and beta-blockers also increase the amount of nitric oxide in the blood, which relaxes the blood vessels and helps to decrease blood pressure. Diuretics and blood pressure medications help to decrease the amount of sodium and fluid in the body, which can help to decrease blood pressure. However, there are side effects to using some diuretics and blood pressure medications, and some diuretics can have an adverse effect on kidney function.'

About one in every three people is diagnosed with high blood pressure. High blood pressure is a major cause of heart attack and stroke. About 8 million people die of heart disease each year, and high blood pressure is a major cause.\n\nCertain drugs, such as antimalarial drugs, aspirin, steroids and some antidepressants, may increase the risk of getting high blood pressure. Smoking, particularly when smoked alongside alcohol, can increase the risk of getting high blood pressure. Diet and physical inactivity may also increase the risk of getting high blood pressure.\n\nHigh blood pressure is often thought of as a silent killer. It does not cause symptoms in many cases. To test for high blood pressure, a person will have their blood pressure measured at the doctor's office. A physician can prescribe medication to lower blood pressure if it is elevated."

Generated text: '\nYou can take an over-the-counter (OTC) bronchodilator for bronchiolitis, such as albuterol (Proventil®). However, a doctor may prescribe a steroid, like prednisone or flonase, to help relieve bronchial inflammation. A doctor may also prescribe a corticosteroid to use for a short time or as a long-term treatment.\n\nThe most effective bronchodilators for bronchiolitis include albuterol (Proventil®) and terbutaline (Terbinafine®). It may take several weeks for the inhaler to work. If you stop taking the medication without telling your doctor, your bronchial inflammation may return.\n\nIf you are prescribed an oral steroid for bronchiolitis, take the medication as directed. You may take the medication with or without food. If you stop taking the medication without telling your doctor, your bronchial inflammation may return.\n\nIf you are prescribed a corticosteroid for bronchiolitis, take the medication as directed. The dose depends on your age, weight, and condition. Your doctor may prescribe a corticosteroid that you inhale, or you may take the medication as an injection.\n\nIf you are prescribed a corticosteroid for bronchiolitis and you are using an inhaled corticosteroid for another condition, such as asthma or allergies, your doctor may prescribe a different type of inhaled corticosteroid.\n\nSome people use inhaled corticosteroids to prevent a flare-up of bronchiolitis. Prompt: 'How can bronchiolitis be prevented?\n' 
Generated text: '\nThere are no simple answers to this question. Many factors play a role in bronchiolitis, including the child’s age, health, and general health of the family.\n\nTo prevent bronchiolitis, talk to your doctor about the importance of regular visits and about vaccines that may help prevent the infection. Here are some other things you can do to help prevent the infection:\n\nMake sure the child is getting enough sleep.\n\nKeep your baby clean by changing diapers and bathing frequently.\n\nKeep a clean environment.\n\nHave the child take baths in warm water.\n\nDo not smoke around your baby.\n\nIf you are a smoker, you should quit smoking now.\n\nWear protective gloves when you handle your baby’s diaper.\n\nEvaluate your child’s cough and keep it from becoming worse. If the cough is red, with a fever, or if the child’s condition worsens, call your doctor.\n\nIf your child is not able to cough up the mucus, call your doctor.\n\nAlways tell the doctor what medications you are using, including herbal supplements.\n\nWhen to Contact a Medical Professional\n\nCall your doctor if your child is having breathing problems.\n\nCall your doctor if your child is having trouble breathing.\n\nCall your doctor if your child does not have a cough but has a fever.\n\nCall your doctor if your child has other signs of bronchiolitis.\n\nHow is Bronchiolitis Diagnosed?\n\nA doctor will listen to your child’s breathing to make sure that he or she is breathing normally. The doctor may also take a history of your child’s symptoms and condition.\n\nHow is Bronchiolitis Treated?\n\nYour child’s health will affect your decision on how to treat the infection. Prompt: 'What is the cause of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease?\n' 
Generated text: "\nCreutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) is caused by a brain-destroying protein called prion. Prions are abnormal proteins that are not very stable and don't self-assemble into a structured protein. Prions contain two strands of nucleotides that are twisted or folded in a way that is not normally found in nature. These abnormal proteins can infect other proteins, forming new, abnormal proteins that are the cause of CJD."

Prompt: 'What are the types of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease?\n' 
Generated text: '\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nIn Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, amyloid beta proteins accumulate in the brain, resulting in a range of symptoms including hallucinations and personality changes. The disease is caused by a missense mutation in the gene for alpha-synuclein, which is present in all cells of the human body.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nCreutzfeldt-Jakob disease is classified according to the type of amyloid deposits in the brain. In early stages of the disease, the deposits appear in the frontal lobe of the brain. These deposits are also called senile plaques. Later on, the deposits appear in the temporal lobe and brain stem. These deposits are called prion plaques. The disease progresses to a late stage when the deposits spread to the spinal cord. The disease is fatal.'

Prompt: 'How is Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease treated?\n' 
Generated text: '\nCJD is a rare, fatal brain disease that attacks the brain and spinal cord. It can occur in people of any age, but it is more common in adults than in children. Early symptoms of CJD include disorientation, slurred speech, changes in personality and hallucinations. These symptoms tend to worsen over time.\n\nPatients who have CJD often have a combination of these symptoms, so it is important to see a doctor as soon as possible. The longer the disease goes untreated, the more severe the symptoms become. In some cases, the disease can be treated with antithrombotics and anti-inflammatory drugs. The disease can also be managed with physical or occupational therapy.\n\nIf a patient has CJD, it is important to monitor his or her symptoms and keep a close eye on any new symptoms. The longer the disease goes untreated, the more severe the symptoms become.\n\nIn many cases, CJD is not treated. However, if the disease is identified early and the patient responds to treatment, the prognosis can be good.'

Prompt: 'What are some of the ways to diagnose HIV?\n' 
Generated text: "\nA:\n\nQuick Answer\n\nSome of the ways to diagnose HIV include blood tests, blood tests for antibodies and HIV tests using antigen detection technology. Antibodies are proteins that the body produces to fight off an infection. In some cases, the body produces antibodies that are also HIV antibodies. HIV tests using antigen detection technology measure the presence of HIV proteins in the body.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nIn addition to blood tests, blood tests for antibodies can be used to diagnose HIV. The blood test for antibodies is a test that determines whether or not the body has produced antibodies to HIV. Antibodies can be used to detect HIV in a person who has not been infected. Antibodies are produced by the immune system to fight off an infection. In some cases, the body produces antibodies that are also HIV antibodies. The HIV test for antibodies is an ELISA blood test. ELISA is an acronym for Enzyme-Linked Immunosorbent Assay. The ELISA test uses a synthetic viral antigen and the body's antibodies to detect the presence of HIV.\n\nThe HIV test for antibodies is a quick blood test that takes 10 to 15 minutes. The test is also used to determine the body's response to anti-HIV medications. The test is helpful in determining whether or not a person is infected with HIV.\n\nA new HIV test using antigen detection technology can be used to diagnose HIV. The test measures the presence of HIV proteins in the blood. The test is used in conjunction with other HIV tests to determine the presence of HIV infection. HIV tests using antigen detection technology are usually accurate, but they are not used for diagnoses because they are not as accurate as ELISA tests."

Multiple sclerosis (MS) is an autoimmune disease that can cause numbness, pain, vision problems and fatigue, among other symptoms. It affects the central nervous system, which is made up of the brain and spinal cord. MS is believed to be caused by the body's immune system attacking myelin, a protective coating that surrounds and insulates the nerves in the brain and spinal cord. MS affects people of all races, ethnicities, genders and ages, and there is no known cure. In the UK, the MS Society estimates that there are around 2,400 new cases every year. It's unclear what triggers an autoimmune reaction in MS, but it is thought that a combination of factors leads to the disease. Prompt: 'What is considered high blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: '\nHow high your blood pressure is can vary depending on your age, gender, weight, and other medical conditions. For most people, when blood pressure reaches 140/90, it\'s considered high. But high blood pressure also can be defined differently for different age groups and genders, so it\'s important to talk to your doctor about your blood pressure.\n\nHigh blood pressure also is sometimes called hypertension. But "hypertension" can be misleading because it can describe a range of blood pressure levels, from 140/90 to 180/120. Talk to your doctor about your blood pressure if it\'s above 140/90.\n\nTo find out if you have high blood pressure, your doctor may perform a simple, noninvasive blood test.\n\nHigh blood pressure can be treated. Talk to your doctor about ways you can lower your blood pressure and reduce your risk for stroke and heart attack.\n\nPeople with high blood pressure who have not yet had a stroke or heart attack can delay treatment, if they wish. But if your blood pressure is above 140/90, you should start taking medication to lower your blood pressure.\n\nAll EBSCO Publishing proprietary, consumer health and medical information found on this site is accredited by URAC. Over time, blood flow to the kidneys is reduced, which can lead to kidney failure. High blood pressure may also affect the inner lining of the blood vessels, which can cause the blood vessels to become swollen. High blood pressure can also lead to clots in the arteries, which can clog the blood vessels.\n\nPeople with high blood pressure are more likely to develop coronary artery disease than people who do not have high blood pressure. Coronary artery disease is the narrowing of the arteries that supply blood to the heart. High blood pressure can increase the chances of having a heart attack or stroke, according to Mayo Clinic.\n\nHigh blood pressure can also lead to peripheral artery disease, which is a disease of the arteries that supply blood to the lower limbs. Peripheral artery disease may cause pain, swelling or numbness in the arms or legs. People with high blood pressure are also more likely to develop an irregular heartbeat or a heart attack, according to Mayo Clinic.\n\nIt is important for people with high blood pressure to receive treatment to help lower their blood pressure. Lowering high blood pressure can reduce the risk of heart disease, heart attacks and strokes. According to the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, controlling high blood pressure can improve a person's overall health."

A BMI of 25 or more is considered overweight. Lowering your BMI can also help you reduce your risk for diabetes and heart disease. It is also important to eat a healthy diet that includes plenty of whole grains and fruits and vegetables. Focus on eating a variety of foods and avoiding fried or starchy foods, as well as alcohol.\n\nLimit salt. High salt intake has been shown to increase blood pressure. These can be used to treat mild cases of bronchitis or as an aid to help people who are not able to take other medicines.\n\nBronchitis medication. It is most noticeable on the upper part of the voice box, near the neck. It may also be found along the sides and back of the neck.\n\nWhat causes laryngite?\n\nThe laryngite membrane is often present when the voice box is irritated by the surrounding tissues or by the voice box itself. When this occurs, a process called inflammation occurs, causing thick, sticky mucus to build up.\n\nHow is laryngite treated?\n\nTreatment for laryngite usually involves modifying your routine so that you do not irritate the voice box. Sometimes medications may be prescribed. The goal is to get rid of the irritating substance that is causing the thick, sticky mucus to build up in the voice box.\n\nWhat should I do if I have laryngite?\n\nIf you have laryngite, be sure to let your physician know. symptoms?\nThere are no specific symptoms to look out for and the condition is usually diagnosed through regular blood pressure checks at your GP surgery.\nHigh blood pressure symptoms\nIt is not possible to tell if you have high blood pressure just by looking at your blood pressure reading.\nInstead, your doctor will take a blood pressure reading by putting a cuff around your upper arm and measuring the pressure inside the cuff.\nA higher pressure reading means that the blood is flowing through your arteries in a faster and more turbulent way, which can put extra strain on your heart and brain.\nWhat causes it?\nIt is impossible to say for sure what causes high blood pressure.\nIt is thought that high blood pressure is caused by an imbalance of hormones in the body, which can be caused by stress, poor diet, lack of exercise, smoking and drinking too much alcohol.\nIt can also be caused by a problem with a vein in the brain or a blockage of the arteries which lead to the heart.\nIt is also possible that high blood pressure is an inherited condition.\nWhat are the risks associated with it?\nHigh blood pressure can lead to strokes, heart attacks and kidney failure if left untreated.\nIt is thought that one in four people will die of a heart attack or stroke over the course of their lives, with high blood pressure one of the biggest risk factors.\nThe risk of Prompt: 'How is high blood pressure diagnosed and what is considered the ideal blood pressure?\n' 
Generated text: 'There are many ways to diagnose high blood pressure. Doctors use different blood tests to determine if high blood pressure is present. Blood tests can measure the amount of salt and fluid in your blood. The results can also show how much blood is being pumped around your body.\nYou will also be asked to complete a health history and answer questions about your health. High blood pressure is considered when the blood pressure is 140/90mm Hg or higher. This is the ideal blood pressure.\nHigh blood pressure can be caused by a number of different factors. Some of these factors can be inherited, while others are not.\nWhen blood pressure is high, it means that your heart has to work harder to pump blood through your body. This is because high blood pressure can cause blood to leak from your blood vessel walls. This leak can cause a stroke when the blood clots.\nThere are many types of high blood pressure. The best treatment for hypertensive crisis is to lower your blood pressure with medications and exercise.\nThis is when your blood pressure rises quickly. The reason this happens is not known. Generated text: '“The best way to reduce blood pressure is to reduce salt in your diet,” said Dr. David Katz, director of the Yale-Griffin Prevention Research Center. “But if you want to supplement and support your efforts, a potassium-rich diet, which can come from a variety of sources, including potatoes, bananas, green leafy vegetables and fruits, is helpful.”\nHigh blood pressure is a major risk factor for heart disease and stroke. It’s called hypertension when blood pressure exceeds 130/80 mmHg, or when it exceeds 140/90 mmHg.\nHigh blood pressure usually is associated with age, ethnic background and a family history of hypertension, among other things. It is treatable, and the American Heart Association recommends at least 150/90 mmHg for most people.\nMany people who have high blood pressure don’t know it.\n“The main way people with high blood pressure can be diagnosed is through an electrocardiogram,” said Dr. Robert Glatter, an emergency physician at Lenox Hill Hospital in New York City. “If you have high blood pressure and you experience chest pain, a rapid heartbeat or shortness of breath, then that’s when you should contact a physician.”\nThe AHA says most people with high blood pressure can reduce it by making some lifestyle changes:\nExercise regularly.\nEat a healthy diet low in sodium and saturated fat.\nLose weight if you are overweight.\nStop smoking.\nStress reduction.\nIf you have high blood pressure and you have a family history of it, ask your doctor about a more intensive program to help you lower your blood pressure.\n“There are a number of medicines available to help lower blood pressure, and the best way to lower your blood pressure is to reduce your salt intake,” Katz said. “But if you find that your diet is still not low enough in salt, and you’re trying to supplement, then a potassium-rich diet can help.”\nThe American Heart Association recommends 2,300 milligrams of potassium a day for most people, but if you are a woman who is pregnant or trying to become pregnant, you need 3,400 milligrams a day.\n“Make sure to check with your doctor to make sure you’re getting the correct amount of potassium,” Glatter said.\nIf you want to add a potassium-rich supplement to your diet, choose one that is 100 percent natural, and preferably certified organic, according to the National Institutes of Health.\n“There are a number of potassium-rich foods that are also relatively low in calories,” Katz said. “But if you’re interested in taking a supplement, the best way to do that is with a potassium-rich capsule.”\nContact reporter Jolene Cleaver at 315-792-4956 or follow her on Twitter (@OD_Cleaver).'

Prompt: 'How is bronchiolitis treated?\n' 
Generated text: "\nBronchiolitis is treated by rest, hydration, and proper administration of medication. Sometimes bronchial tubes need to be removed surgically. Bronchiolitis is also treated with the use of a nebulizer.\n\nA nebulizer is a device that delivers medicine directly into the lungs through a tube. A nebulizer has a long, flexible tube. The tube is connected to a box that holds medicine and other chemicals. The box is connected to the tube by a valve. When you breathe in, the valve opens, allowing the medicine to flow into the tube. You then breathe out, and the valve closes. This allows the medicine to flow through the tube into the lungs.\n\nFor some children with bronchiolitis, breathing treatments are all that is necessary to relieve the symptoms of bronchiolitis. For others, treatment with medication and a nebulizer is required.\n\nYou should always tell your doctor if your child has ever had a surgery. If your child has ever had an infection, please also tell your doctor.\n\nThe best way to help your child with bronchiolitis is to make sure he or she is getting plenty of rest. Your child should not be kept awake for more than a few hours at a time. After a few days, your child will probably be able to go back to school.\n\nIf your child cannot go back to school because of bronchiolitis, you may want to make sure he or she is getting lots of rest at home. A child who is getting plenty of rest at home may need a little help with schoolwork, but this should not keep your child from getting enough rest.\n\nSince your child may not be able to go back to school, you should make sure that he or she is getting lots of exercise. This will help your child to take medicine without feeling too sick.\n\nIf your child has never had a surgery, your doctor will want to run some tests. Tests will be done to make sure that there is no infection. Your doctor may want to test your child's sputum, blood, and urine. A chest x-ray is sometimes done on children with bronchiolitis.\n\nYour doctor may also want to do a physical exam. The doctor will use a stethoscope to listen to your child's lungs. Prions cannot be destroyed by normal enzymes. Prions do not cause any symptoms until they infect brain cells. This can happen in many different ways.\n\nCJD is not contagious. Prompt: 'What is a heart attack?\n' 
Generated text: '\nA heart attack is a serious medical emergency that occurs when there is a sudden blockage of one or more of the arteries that carry blood to the heart.\n\nA heart attack is serious because it can quickly and severely damage the heart muscle. It can also cause the heart to stop beating.\n\nA heart attack is a medical emergency and should always be treated as such.\n\nSymptoms of a heart attack\n\nThere are different types of heart attacks that may cause different symptoms. If you experience any of the following symptoms, you should see a doctor immediately:\n\nChest pain\n\nShortness of breath\n\nNausea or vomiting\n\nDizziness\n\nWeakness\n\nLightheadedness or fainting\n\nThis is not a complete list of symptoms, but they are the most common symptoms.\n\nCauses of heart attacks\n\nHeart attacks can occur when one or more of the arteries that carry blood to the heart becomes blocked. When this happens, blood cannot reach the heart. This can cause serious problems with the heart and may be fatal.\n\nThe following are the most common causes of heart attacks:\n\nBlockage of an artery in the coronary arteries. These are the main arteries that supply blood to the heart muscle. They become blocked when plaque builds up in them.\n\nBlockage of an artery in the peripheral arteries. These are the arteries that carry blood to the legs. Blockage of these arteries can cause a heart attack in the legs.\n\nBlockage of any of the tiny blood vessels in the heart. This can cause a heart attack in the heart muscle.\n\nA heart attack can be caused by other conditions that cause the heart muscle to swell. These include high blood pressure, an enlarged heart, a thickened heart wall, or a blockage in the coronary arteries.\n\nDiagnosis of a heart attack\n\nTo diagnose a heart attack, your doctor will ask about your symptoms and medical history. A physical exam will be done to check your heart. Blood tests will be done to check your blood pressure, cholesterol, and other medical conditions.\n\nYour doctor will also perform a heart catheterization (also known as an angiogram) to check your heart.\n\nThis is a procedure in which a thin, flexible tube (catheter) is passed through an opening in the groin, arm, or neck into the coronary arteries. A dye is injected into the arteries and then a special x-ray technique is used to visualize the arteries and see if they are blocked.\n\nThe angiogram may be repeated if the doctor needs to see the arteries at different angles to better view the blockage.\n\nAfter the angiogram, your doctor will discuss the results with you and give you a diagnosis. He or she may suggest other tests, such as:\n\nOther imaging tests, such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI)\n\nBlood tests, such as a troponin test\n\nA stress test, in which your heart is tested to see how it responds to a series of tests\n\nLaparoscopic (keyhole) heart surgery, in which an incision is made in the abdomen and a tiny camera is passed through the incision to view the heart\n\nStents are small, mesh-like devices that are placed in an artery to keep the artery open. They can be used in people who have had a heart attack to help clear the blockage.\n\nTreatment of a heart attack\n\nTreatment of a heart attack depends on the severity of the condition and can include:\n\nPrescription medications.\n\nPhysical therapy.\n\nSurgery.\n\nThese treatments are intended to reduce the pain, reduce damage to the heart muscle, and help the heart recover.\n\nA heart attack can be treated immediately by calling 911 (or the local emergency number) and by seeking medical care. This will help reduce the risk of death.\n\nIf you have a heart attack at home, you should immediately call for help.\n\nYou should lie down or sit with your knees bent so that blood can flow into your legs. Do not try to get up.\n\nHold a cloth or a towel to the side of your face to keep it from closing.\n\nIf you are having chest pain, take some of the following steps:\n\nStay calm and stay still. Do not move around, as this will make the pain worse.\n\nDo not take any medications.\n\nDo not take aspirin.\n\nIf you have difficulty breathing or shortness of breath, call 911 or go to the hospital.\n\nIf you have chest pain and feel lightheaded or faint, call 911 or go to the hospital.\n\nWhen to see a doctor\n\nIf you have a heart attack, it is important to seek medical care as soon as possible.\n\nIt is best to see a doctor as soon as possible after a heart attack. This will help your doctor know'

Prompt: 'What causes a heart attack?\n' 
Generated text: '\nShare this page\n\nHeart attacks are caused when blood flow to the heart is reduced or blocked. This causes the heart muscle to die off and deprives it of oxygen. This can be due to a build-up of cholesterol in the coronary arteries. When blood flow to the heart is reduced, the heart muscle cells are damaged and die, depriving the heart of blood and oxygen. This leaves the heart muscle starved of oxygen and unable to perform its job. It stops pumping blood around the body and eventually causes the heart to stop beating.\n\nOnce blood flow to the heart has been restored, the heart muscle cells are able to grow back and contract again, and the heart can start pumping blood again.\n\nPeople who have heart attacks are usually treated in hospital by a cardiologist (heart doctor) or a cardiologist and a surgeon. The aim of treatment is to restore blood flow to the heart and to help the heart muscle to grow back and contract again.'

Some steroids are very toxic to the liver.\n\nFor the treatment of asthma, one can use corticosteroids. However, these are used only short term. Corticosteroids can be used only in the short term.\n\nCorticosteroids are used to treat mild asthma.\n\nHowever, for severe asthma, it is important to use inhaled steroid drugs. These drugs can be used for several weeks or months.\n\nThe side effects of inhaled steroids are fewer compared to those of oral steroids.\n\nThere are also safer alternative drugs available, which are used to treat asthma.\n\nAbout the Author\n\nNamrata is a Medical Writer for ProHealth, providing health information on various topics to both consumers and healthcare professionals. Prompt: 'What is HIV?\n' 
Generated text: '\nHIV, or Human Immunodeficiency Virus, is a virus that attacks the immune system. When a person has HIV, their immune system is unable to fight off infections and diseases. The virus causes a wide variety of symptoms and medical problems.\n\nAn HIV infection can be spread through sexual contact. HIV is also spread through the blood of an infected person, or through infected blood products, such as blood transfusions. It is possible to become infected if a needle sticks into the body and the blood from an infected person enters a vein or tissue in the body.\n\nHow does HIV enter the body?\n\nThe most common way that HIV is spread is through sexual contact. This is especially common if both partners have an HIV infection.\n\nHowever, people with HIV can become infected through the following other ways:\n\nBlood transfusions. When people have HIV, it is possible for the virus to be passed on in the blood. This can happen when a blood product is used by someone who is infected. This can include blood transfusions or donations.\n\nBlood products. It is possible that infected blood products can be used to treat or prevent infections in other people. This is especially likely to happen if the product is infected during the process of collecting it.\n\nHIV is spread through the blood of infected people, such as those who have HIV and people who have HIV but do not know it. In addition, HIV can be spread through the blood of an infected person who is giving blood. The risk of transmission of HIV from a donor to another person is greater for people who have been given blood products (blood transfusions or donations), because the virus can be passed on in the blood. The risk is also greater for women who have had a pregnancy terminated by a procedure involving the use of a blood product or a person who has a blood disease.\n\nHow is HIV treated?\n\nHIV can be treated, but the treatment must be started early to prevent the virus from becoming a chronic problem. The earlier treatment is started, the better the chances of preventing the virus from spreading.\n\nAn HIV infection that is left untreated can lead to severe illness, and even death. A person with HIV who has an undetectable level of the virus in their blood cannot pass it on to anyone else.\n\nTreatment for HIV can be complicated, so people with HIV and their doctors should work closely together to decide on the best treatment plan. Treatment is usually started with a combination of medicines, called combination therapy, to lower the amount of virus in the body. The medicines used depend on the person\'s condition, but the medicines used most often are:\n\nHIV-1 protease inhibitors (tenofovir, emtricitabine, and efavirenz)\n\nHIV-1 reverse transcriptase inhibitors (viread, emtricitabine, and darunavir)\n\nHIV-1 integrase inhibitors (cobicistat, dolutegravir, and raltegravir)\n\nHIV-2 protease inhibitors (cobicistat, dolutegravir, and raltegravir)\n\nHIV-2 reverse transcriptase inhibitors (Truvada, Elvitegravir, and Reyataz)\n\nAntiretroviral drugs. These medicines are used together to help keep the amount of virus in the body low, and to prevent it from becoming resistant to the medicines.\n\nSome people with HIV may not need any medicine at all, or may only need to take one medicine at a time. There are also some medicines that are not recommended for people with HIV.\n\nSome people with HIV require additional medicines for some of the medical problems caused by HIV. These medicines are not needed every day.\n\nTalk to your doctor about which medicines to take, and when. This is called an "undetectable" viral load.\n\nThere are two different tests that can be used to measure the amount of HIV in the blood.\n\nThe first is a "sensitivity" test. This is done by looking for signs of HIV in blood samples that have been tested for other infections.\n\nThe second is a "specificity" test. This is done by looking for signs of HIV in blood samples that have not been tested for other infections.\n\nThe results of both tests are compared, and a score is given to indicate how likely it is that'

Prompt: 'What should people with HIV do to live a healthy life?\n' 
Generated text: '\nMore than three million people in the United States have HIV. Many people think that living with HIV is a death sentence, but the truth is, thanks to the work of dedicated medical professionals, many people with HIV can live long, healthy lives. In fact, it is possible to live a long, healthy life with HIV, but it requires a lifestyle change and the use of medications.\n\nTake antiretroviral medications\n\nAntiretroviral medications are the most important tool that people living with HIV use to prevent the virus from progressing to AIDS. Without antiretroviral medications, HIV can attack and destroy the immune system. Without a functioning immune system, HIV can cause serious health problems. People with HIV who use antiretroviral medications will not develop AIDS. In fact, some studies show that people with HIV who use antiretroviral medications have a lower risk of developing AIDS than those who do not.\n\nTake antiretroviral medications as prescribed\n\nPeople who have HIV need to take their medication on a daily basis. It is important to follow the directions on the medication package because it will help prevent resistance to the medications. Do not stop taking the medication without first talking with your doctor. Stopping the medication can cause you to develop an illness called viral resistance. Viral resistance is a type of HIV resistance that occurs when the virus has mutated and becomes resistant to the medication. This is a serious problem because it can lead to a condition called HIV-1 drug-resistant infection (HIV-DRI). HIV-DRI is an infection caused by a virus that is resistant to all three of the drugs used to treat HIV.\n\nUse condoms\n\nThe best way to prevent HIV is to have as many sexual partners as you like. The problem is that sexual activity is much more complicated than that. People with HIV are more likely to transmit HIV during sex if they do not use a condom. People with HIV should use condoms every time they have sex, no matter what the person’s HIV status is.\n\nCarry a test kit\n\nPeople with HIV should carry a test kit with them at all times. The test kit is a small plastic device that allows people to test their own blood for HIV. The test kit is easy to use and it will help you find out if you have HIV or not. If the test comes back positive, the test kit can help you find out if the HIV is being passed to a sexual partner.\n\nStay healthy\n\nYou can live a long, healthy life with HIV, but it will require a lifestyle change. You need to take your medication every day, and you need to wear a condom every time you have sex. Also, you need to take care of yourself. Eat healthy food, get plenty of rest, and exercise regularly. This will help you to fight off the virus that is trying to kill you.\n\nYou can live a long, healthy life with HIV. The truth is that people with HIV can live long, happy, healthy lives. However, it will take a lifestyle change and the use of antiretroviral medications to help people with HIV live a healthy life.\n\nThis information is not intended to replace the advice of a doctor. Prompt: 'What is laryngitis?\n' 
Generated text: '\nLaryngitis is an inflammation of the vocal cords. The voicebox is located in the throat, and the soft tissue and surrounding muscles and bones are connected by the vocal cords. When the larynx becomes inflamed, the voice is muffled, hoarse, and strained.\n\nCauses\n\nThe main cause of laryngitis is viral infections. Common viruses that can cause laryngitis include the cold, flu, and adenovirus. In addition, a common cause of laryngitis is allergic reaction. During a severe allergic reaction, the body’s immune system reacts to the allergen and causes inflammation and swelling in the throat. Other possible causes of laryngitis include smoking, bad posture, and use of antibiotics.\n\nSymptoms\n\nThe symptoms of laryngitis usually begin gradually and worsen over a period of weeks or months. The symptoms may include hoarseness, sore throat, and a change in the voice. Swallowing difficulty is also very common, and people may find that they have trouble breathing. The throat may feel irritated or painful to the touch, and inflammation of the vocal cords may produce a crackling sound.\n\nTreatment\n\nLaryngitis can be treated at home, but symptoms may worsen if left untreated. If you experience a sore throat, your doctor may prescribe over-the-counter throat lozenges or antihistamines. You should also use a humidifier at night to help prevent swelling in your throat and reduce the inflammation. Staying hydrated can also help to reduce swelling.\n\nWhile over-the-counter treatments are often sufficient, some cases of laryngitis are more severe and require medical treatment. In these cases, your doctor may prescribe antibiotics to treat a bacterial infection. In severe cases, laryngitis may need to be treated with surgery, though the surgeon may recommend a procedure called a laryngeal shave, where the vocal cords are separated from each other.\n\nPrevention\n\nYou can prevent laryngitis by avoiding smoking and using a humidifier to help reduce swelling in your throat.\n\nRevision Information\n\nThis content is reviewed regularly and is updated when new and relevant evidence is made available. This information is neither intended nor implied to be a substitute for professional medical advice. Always seek the advice of your physician or other qualified health provider prior to starting any new treatment or with questions regarding a medical condition.'

Laryngitis is generally not dangerous and can be treated with over-the-counter cough or throat lozenges and a humidifier.\n\nKeep Learning\n\nSymptoms of laryngitis include a runny nose, scratchy throat, hoarseness, dry cough and difficulty breathing. This is most often caused by a viral infection, such as the common cold or flu. Laryngitis can be dangerous and may lead to a sinus infection, pneumonia, sore throat, hearing loss, permanent hearing loss and permanent damage to the vocal cords, according to WebMD. Laryngitis is more serious if it occurs in children and adults who are already suffering from asthma, emphysema, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, chronic bronchitis or chronic idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis, WebMD notes.\n\nLaryngitis can also be caused by a bacterial infection. This is more common in children who have allergies or food sensitivities. These infections are usually treated with antibiotics.\n\nTreatment for laryngitis generally involves rest and over-the-counter medications. Rest is recommended to allow the inflammation to go down and prevent permanent damage to the vocal cords.'

Prompt: "Qu'est-ce que le VIH?\n" 
Generated text: '\nWhat is the HIV virus?\n\nHuman Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is the virus that causes acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS).\n\nAIDS is a syndrome that is marked by the inability of the immune system to fight off infection, resulting in an increased susceptibility to opportunistic infections. In some people, AIDS progresses to a severe, fatal disease called acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) or acquired immune deficiency syndrome (AIDS).\n\nThere are three types of HIV: HIV-1, HIV-2, and HIV-3. Most people are infected with HIV-1. The HIV-1 virus has a high rate of mutation, and different types of HIV-1 (or subtypes) circulate in the population.\n\nPeople who are infected with HIV-1 can have symptoms of HIV infection at any stage of HIV disease progression. HIV-1 infection can occur at any age, although the majority of people are infected between the ages of 15 and 45.\n\nHow does HIV infection occur?\n\nHIV infection occurs when a person has sex with someone who is infected with HIV. A person with HIV can pass the infection to others through unprotected sexual contact. The virus can also be spread through blood and other body fluids (e.g., breast milk) if a person with HIV has an open sore on their body and the other person touches that sore, or if they share needles.\n\nHow is HIV diagnosed?\n\nBlood and other body fluid tests are used to diagnose HIV infection. A person with HIV can have symptoms of HIV infection at any stage of HIV disease progression. HIV-1 infection can occur at any age, although the majority of people are infected between the ages of 15 and 45.\n\nHow is HIV treated?\n\nThere are no medicines that cure HIV infection. People living with HIV take medicines to prevent infection from spreading to other people. HIV medicines also help treat and control symptoms.\n\nTreating HIV\n\nThe HIV medicines called antiretroviral drugs (ARVs) are taken by mouth. ARVs work by reducing the amount of virus in the body.\n\nIn the United States, antiretroviral drugs are available for people at risk for HIV infection. HIV medicines are also available for people with HIV infection.'

Prompt: 'Qui peut diagnostiquer la sclérose en plaques?\n' 
Generated text: "\nLa sclérose en plaques (SSP) est un trouble de l'organisme des gens ayant un état de santé sévère. La plaques sclérose sont des tissus non-cellulaires en forme de nids qui créent une entrave à l'intégration et aux activités des cellules cellules de l'organisme. La plaques sclérose se développent par le processus de sclérose mutagenique. Les patients souffrant de SSP ont une faible capacité à se loger, à respirer, à manger, à se masturber, à écrire, à se sentir et à exprimer des sentiments. Les causes de la sclérose en plaques sont différentes selon le niveau de sclérose.\n\nDans certains cas, il existe la possibilité de diagnostiquer la sclérose en plaques en utilisant des tests de laboratoire. Dans d'autres cas, le patient en est déjà conscient. Quelque chose est sûr, la sclérose en plaques augmente progressivement au cours des années et peut devenir préoccupante. Dans le cas des patients en état de sclérose sévère, il est possible d'évaluer leur état en recourant à des tests de laboratoire et de recherche.\n\nQuels sont les tests de laboratoire utilisés pour diagnostiquer la sclérose en plaques?\n\nCes tests de laboratoire sont utilisés par les médecins et sont des moyens de diagnostiquer les troubles de l'organisme. Les tests de laboratoire utilisés pour diagnostiquer la sclérose en plaques sont cependant plus nombreux que ceux utilisés pour évaluer d'autres pathologies.\n\nLe test de laboratoire à base d'une biopsy (biopsie d'une partie du corps) est utilisé pour diagnostiquer la sclérose en plaques. La biopsy d'une partie du corps est pratiquée en utilisant des petites pelles de tissus non-cellulaires de la plaques sclérose qui sont séparées et analysées au laboratoire. Les médecins utilisent deux types de biopsie. La première est la biopsy directe avec une ligne de foin et une réaction.
